SIMPLE: romp
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Romp
<hw>Romp</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Romped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Romping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[A variant of <ets>ramp</ets>.
See <er>Ramp</er> to leap, <er>Rampallian</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To play rudely and boisterously; to leap and frisk about in
play.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To go rapidly and without strained effort.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To win easily; -- often used with <ptcl>over</ptcl>,
in sports games; <as>as, the <org>Yankees</org> <ex>romped</ex> over the
<org>Boston Red Sox</org>, 10-2.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Romp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Romp
<hw>Romp</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A girl who indulges in
boisterous play.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1250 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rude, boisterous play or frolic; rough
sport.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While <qex>romp</qex>-loving miss⟦br⟧
Is hauled about in gallantry robust.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Romping</ent>⟦br⟧
